            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Nia Khademi\u2019s world was forged in the heat of two distinct kitchens. Raised in Atlanta, she was the only child of a meticulous Iranian architect father and a warm, gregarious Black librarian mother. Their home was a constant, fragrant negotiation between her father\u2019s saffron-laced tahdig and her mother\u2019s rich, soulful Southern cooking. For Nia, hospitality wasn't a choice; it was an inheritance. She saw how a well-prepared meal could bridge cultures and create community, a lesson she absorbed deeply.\n\nHer path seemed pre-written. She earned a Bachelor's in Hospitality and Tourism Management from Georgia State University, excelling in the practical, high-pressure environment. She cut her teeth in Atlanta's burgeoning restaurant scene, quickly ascending from server to floor manager. But she felt a ceiling approaching. At 29, a prestigious San Francisco restaurant group recruited her for an Assistant General Manager position. It was a terrifying leap, trading the comfort of home for the notorious demands of the Bay Area\u2019s culinary world. The key turning point was realizing she feared regret more than failure.\n\nNow, at 41, Nia is the General Manager of \"Cypress,\" a Michelin-starred establishment in Hayes Valley. Her life is a rhythm of late nights and early mornings, a controlled chaos she navigates with practiced grace. Her apartment is a mere 0.7-mile walk away, a commute she cherishes as a time to decompress, observing the city's pulse before immersing herself in the restaurant's symphony of service. Her social circle is tight-knit, composed mainly of other industry veterans who understand the sacrifice her career demands; a long-term relationship ended years ago under the strain of her commitment to her work.\n\nLiving in Hayes Valley, she feels intrinsically linked to the city's artistic heart, with the symphony and opera houses as her neighbors. San Francisco isn't just her home; it's the arena where she proves her mettle nightly. Her dream, however, is taking root. Nia aspires to open her own restaurant one day\u2014not another temple of fine dining, but a smaller, intimate space that finally fuses the two sides of her culinary soul: the bold, comforting flavors of the American South with the intricate, fragrant traditions of Persia."
        },
